I have standardised the possessive of Paris throughout to Paris's. There was a varied use of Paris' and Paris's through the article. In English the possessive of Paris is pronounced Paris-iz, hence there is no need to displace the normal rule that the possessive in English is formed with 's, including for singular nouns ending in s. There are some historical exceptions, eg Jesus', Achilles' and some entenched usage example that drop the second s, but Paris is not amongst these exceptions. ~~~~
